me of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":31,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":40,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnes de Legh was born in 1184, in High Legh, Cheshire, England, her father, Richard de Legh - Lord of West Hall and High Leigh, was 24 and her mother, Margery de Holgrave, was -13. She married William Tabley about 1200, in Cheshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1240, in her hometown, at the age of 56."},"et":{"1184–1240":"1184–1240","1211–Male":"1211–Surnud","1217–Male":"1217–Surnud","1227–Female":"1227–Surnud","1190–1240":"1190–1240","1215–1254":"1215–1254","1160–1250":"1160–1250","1197–1275":"1197–1275","1190":"1190